"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713531","Home Office","false","2017-03-30","<p>The total numbers of transfer of firearms into the UK by registered importers from the EU for the last five years is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>Total number of transfers</p><p> </p><ul><li>April 2012 – March 2013 2,458</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>April 2013 – March 2014 4,969</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>April 2014 – March 2015 3,528</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>April 2015 – March 2016 4,231</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>April 2016 – March 2017 3,692 (up to 21<sup>st</sup> March 2017)</li></ul><p> </p><p>These figures represent the number of commercial movements. The total numbers of firearms from these transfers have not routinely been collated albeit the information is held on each record.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-03-30T12:56:15.533Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713531/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713531/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713531/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-23","Firearms: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many firearms have been imported into the UK by registered importers from other countries within the EU in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","68900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713532","Home Office","false","2017-03-30","<p>Guidance on which groups of EU nationals require comprehensive sickness insurance as well as the types of documents accepted to meet this condition has always been publicly available to all parties. This can currently be found from page 30 onwards of the guidance on ‘qualified persons’ available on the GOV.UK website via the link below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/european-economic-area-nationals-qualified-persons" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/european-economic-area-nationals-qualified-persons</a></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","68897","2017-03-30T14:18:04.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713532/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713532/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713532/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-23","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what guidance her Department provides to universities and colleges on the requirement for comprehensive sickness insurance for EU citizens from outside the UK.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","68896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713533","Home Office","false","2017-03-30","<p>Guidance on which groups of EU nationals require comprehensive sickness insurance as well as the types of documents accepted to meet this condition has always been publicly available to all parties. This can currently be found from page 30 onwards of the guidance on ‘qualified persons’ available on the GOV.UK website via the link below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/european-economic-area-nationals-qualified-persons" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/european-economic-area-nationals-qualified-persons</a></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","68896","2017-03-30T14:18:04.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713533/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713533/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713533/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-23","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what guidance her Department provides for insurance providers and non-UK EU citizens who plan to be resident in the UK on what qualifies as comprehensive sickness insurance.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","68897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713534","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-29","<p>Under the Dogs (Protection of Livestock) Act 1953, the maximum penalty for dog attacks on livestock is a fine of up to £1000. Currently there are no plans to increase this penalty.</p><p> </p><p>As part of addressing dog attacks on livestock, Defra and the Animal Health and Welfare Board for England recently met police forces, and farming and rural interests to discuss the situation. Under the auspices of the National Police Chiefs’ Council five police forces are collaborating to pilot good response practices.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-29T13:16:38.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713534/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713534/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713534/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-23","Livestock: Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will consider increasing the penalties for dog attacks on livestock; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","68893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713535","Home Office","false","2017-03-29","<p>The Government published its White Paper, “The United Kingdom’s exit from and new partnership with European Union” on 2 February. It provides a comprehensive articulation of the objectives and the rationale for our approach to the forthcoming negotiations.</p><p> </p><p>As we conduct the negotiations to leave the EU, it must be a priority to regain more control of the numbers of people who come here from Europe.</p><p> </p><p>We are about to begin these negotiations and it would be wrong to set out further positions in advance. At every step of these negotiations we will work to ensure the best possible outcome for the British people.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-29T15:35:32.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713535/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713535/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713535/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-23","Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether reforms to the UK's immigration rules will be within the scope of negotiations on the UK's future relationship with the EU.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","68873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713536","Home Office","false","2017-03-28","<p>The impact on current legislation of the ECJ Judgment of 21<sup>st</sup> Dec 2016 on data retention is still being considered by the Government.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","68847 ; 68857 ; 68876 ; 68877","2017-03-28T16:28:00.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713536/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713536/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713536/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-23","Telecommunications: Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the budget for the independent communications data authorising body will be drawn from existing police budgets.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","68917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713537","Home Office","false","2017-03-30","<p>The Home Office regularly discusses with the National Police Chief’s Council the effectiveness of public order tactics including the use of Mounted Horse Units for crowd control purposes.</p><p> </p><p>Police support animals make an outstanding contribution to the detection and prevention of crime and in maintaining public safety. Decisions on the availability and deployment of horses and mounted units are an operational matter for chief constables, working with their Police and Crime Commissioner.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-03-30T14:17:02.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713537/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713537/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713537/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-23","Police: Horses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department has had discussions with police forces on the retention of horses for use in crowd control.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","68952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713538","Home Office","false","2017-03-28","<p>We are aware of different legislative approaches to prostitution – including in Northern Ireland, where all buying of sex has been criminalised and the selling decriminalised. We have yet to see unequivocal evidence that any one approach is better at tackling harm and exploitation – and that remains our priority. Our laws are there to tackle exploitation and abuse, clamping down on activities such as brothel-keeping and kerb-crawling. We will closely monitor the implementation, enforcement, and impact of the changes in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p>As we set out in the Government's response to the Home Affairs Select Committee (HASC), we are committed to tackling the harm and exploitation that can be associated with prostitution and sex work, and believe that people who want to leave prostitution should be given every opportunity to escape it. Through the Tampon Tax Fund, we are providing a total of £389,000 to organisations which help those who want to leave prostitution and sex work.</p><p> </p><p>The Government funds a victim care contract worth £40 million between 2015-2020 for all identified adult victims of modern slavery, which can include sexual exploitation and forced prostitution, in England and Wales. This is delivered by The Salvation Army through a series of specialist sub-contractors and can include safe accommodation and psychological support.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","68963","2017-03-28T16:21:44.04Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713538/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713538/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713538/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-23","Prostitution: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her most recent assessment is of the potential consequences of implementation and enforcement of Northern Ireland legislation on prostitution for the rest of the UK.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","68962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713539","Home Office","false","2017-03-30","<p>The Home Office does not hold the requested information centrally.</p><p>It is not possible to identify how many crimes were committed by hunt saboteurs from the police recorded crime data held by the Home Office.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-03-30T14:14:34.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713539/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713539/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713539/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-23","Hunt Saboteurs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many incidents involving alleged offences by hunt saboteurs have been reported in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","68949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713540","Home Office","false","2017-03-28","<p>We are aware of different legislative approaches to prostitution – including in Northern Ireland, where all buying of sex has been criminalised and the selling decriminalised. We have yet to see unequivocal evidence that any one approach is better at tackling harm and exploitation – and that remains our priority. Our laws are there to tackle exploitation and abuse, clamping down on activities such as brothel-keeping and kerb-crawling. We will closely monitor the implementation, enforcement, and impact of the changes in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p>As we set out in the Government's response to the Home Affairs Select Committee (HASC), we are committed to tackling the harm and exploitation that can be associated with prostitution and sex work, and believe that people who want to leave prostitution should be given every opportunity to escape it. Through the Tampon Tax Fund, we are providing a total of £389,000 to organisations which help those who want to leave prostitution and sex work.</p><p> </p><p>The Government funds a victim care contract worth £40 million between 2015-2020 for all identified adult victims of modern slavery, which can include sexual exploitation and forced prostitution, in England and Wales. This is delivered by The Salvation Army through a series of specialist sub-contractors and can include safe accommodation and psychological support.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","68962","2017-03-28T16:21:44.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713540/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713540/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713540/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-23","Prostitution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what approaches the Government is piloting for identifying and supporting victims of forced prostitution; and what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of such approaches.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","68963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713541","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-30","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-03-30T10:08:55.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713541/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713541/answer","PQ 68951.pdf","PQ 68951.pdf","Letter from UKSA","Letter from UKSA","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713541/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-23","Knives: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what information his Department holds on the number of assaults carried out by people using knives in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","68951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713542","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-30","<p>The UK Government has stepped up its efforts to play a leading role in improving energy access in developing countries through decentralised renewable energy programmes to help meet the basic energy needs of some of the poorest people in the world.</p><p>For example, our Results Based Financing programme is improving people’s access to modern energy in countries of Africa by speeding up and growing markets for businesses to deliver affordable energy to households.</p><p>Through the UK Government’s International Climate Finance we have so far improved energy access for 6.6 million people in developing countries.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-03-30T14:52:46.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713542/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713542/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713542/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-23","Developing Countries: Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to encourage the development of decentralised renewable energies in developing countries.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","68984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713543","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-30","<p>The UK Government plays a leading role in improving energy access in developing countries through decentralised renewable energy programmes to help meet the basic energy needs of some of the poorest people in the world.</p><p>For example, our Results Based Financing programme is improving people’s access to modern energy in countries of Africa by speeding up and growing markets for businesses to deliver affordable energy to households.</p><p>Through the UK Government’s International Climate Finance we have so far improved energy access for 6.6 million people in developing countries.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-03-30T14:49:47.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713543/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713543/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713543/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-23","Developing Countries: Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will increase funding for the eradication of fuel poverty in developing countries.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","68983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713544","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-28","<p>The UK has led the international response to the humanitarian crisis in North East Nigeria and the Lake Chad Region caused by the conflict with Boko Haram.</p><p>Last year our support reached more than one million people including children, women and the disabled. Where people are able to return, we are providing them with food, water, shelter and health care. We are supporting people to restart their livelihoods and providing solar power to re-establish health centres and schools. We are helping people to understand the risks of explosives left behind in their villages. We are also working with Federal and State Governments to ensure that people are supported while they are displaced and do not return home before it is safe.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-03-28T16:44:47.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713544/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713544/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713544/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-23","Nigeria: Boko Haram","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assistance the Government is giving to people in Nigeria who have begun to return to their home villages after the retreat of Boko Haram.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","68912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713545","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-28","<p>Officials at the Consulate-General in Jerusalem and ministers and officials at the Foreign and Commonwealth Office regularly raise the issue of incitement with Palestinian officials. During his recent visit to the region, the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson), urged President Abbas to ensure the Palestinian Authority does more to tackle incitement. We also raise specific instances where we are concerned that language from senior Palestinian officials is not conducive to peace. We continue to urge Israeli and Palestinian officials to revive the Trilateral Commission on incitement, to deal with specific allegations.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-28T15:39:25.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713545/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713545/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713545/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-23","Palestinians: Incitement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 20 March 2017 to Question 67423, what criteria his Department uses when deciding whether to raise an issue of incitement with the Palestinian Authority.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","68889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713546","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-30","<p>The Department for International Development is supporting ten water, sanitation and hygiene projects that aim to improve nutrition outcomes for women, girls and children across 20 countries: Democratic Republic of Congo, Ethiopia, Ghana, Kenya, Madagascar, Malawi, Mozambique, Niger, South Sudan, Sudan, Tanzania, Uganda, Yemen, Zambia, Zimbabwe, Bangladesh, Cambodia, Myanmar, Nepal and Pakistan.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-03-30T14:48:16.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713546/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713546/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713546/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-23","Developing Countries: Nutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 13 February 2017 to Question 63106, in which countries her Department is strengthening nutrition outcomes of its water, sanitation and hygiene programmes.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","68846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713547","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-30","<p>The Secretary of State has regular discussions with Cabinet colleagues regarding the allocation of UK official development assistance (ODA) to ensure that it is used most effectively to tackle global challenges in our national interest, in line with the UK Aid Strategy.</p><p>The main mechanism for providing UK bilateral ODA in Eastern Europe is the Conflict, Stability and Security Fund (CSSF). This includes support to economic and political reform delivered to five countries – including Moldova, Georgia and Ukraine – through the Good Governance Fund (GGF).</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-03-30T14:45:35.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713547/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713547/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713547/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-23","Eastern Europe: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with Cabinet colleagues on increasing the level of UK aid to Eastern Europe; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","68844"
