"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713579","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-28","<p>Universal Credit supports gainful self-employment for claimants where it is the best possible route for them to become self-sufficient, and the Minimum Income Floor is designed to address flaws in the current system which allow self-employed claimants to receive full State support while declaring low or zero earnings. This situation is unsustainable and unfair on the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>However, we are aware that for the self-employed, including farmers, builders and many other seasonal businesses, their earnings often fluctuate from month to month.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-28T16:01:14.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713579/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713579/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713579/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-23","Universal Credit: Seasonal Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the universal credit minimum income floor on the agricultural sector workers whose income is seasonal; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","68887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713580","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-28","<p>HM Revenue and Customs does not hold such an estimate. Not all customers who fail to submit their return on time will have to pay a penalty, as they may appeal a penalty on the grounds of having had a reasonable excuse for late submission.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-28T15:54:20.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713580/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713580/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713580/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-23","Taxation: Self-assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 15 March 2017 to Question 68122, what estimate he has made of the amount of fines due to be payable as a result of those people who missed the 31 January 2017 deadline for their tax returns.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","68911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713581","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-31","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-31T13:47:03.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713581/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713581/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713581/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-23","Social Security Benefits: Multiple Sclerosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of people with multiple sclerosis on (a) income-based employment and support allowance and (b) the limited capability for the work element of universal credit have received sanctions in the latest year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","68898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713582","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-31","<p>Imposing a sanction is not something we do lightly. Claimants are given every opportunity to explain why they failed to meet their agreed conditionality requirements, before a decision is made.</p><p> </p><p>A sanction reduces a claimant’s Universal Credit award by an amount never more than their standard allowance element entitlement.</p><p> </p><p>A claimant with a health condition or disability, who makes a claim for Universal Credit on or after 3 April 2017, and who is found to have limited capability for work following a WCA, will not be eligible for the limited capability for work element of Universal Credit.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","68957","2017-03-31T11:48:55.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713582/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713582/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713582/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-23","Universal Credit: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what criteria a person would have to meet to receive a sanction equal to the financial support they receive from the limited capability for the work element of universal credit (a) now and (b) from April 2017 following the change in the rate at which that element is paid.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","68901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713583","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-28","<p>Recent changes to the Personal Independence Payment (PIP) regulations clarify the original criteria used to decide how much benefit claimants receive. This is not a policy change, nor is it intended to make new savings. It will not result in any claimants, regardless of their health condition, seeing a reduction in the amount of PIP previously awarded by DWP.</p><p> </p><p>We are aware of a small number of cases, around 50 cases currently, where people may have been awarded a higher level of PIP by a tribunal. This could occur if their case was heard at appeal and a tribunal made a higher award, applying the rulings of the Upper Tribunal. We will not be claiming back the money these individuals received during the period before the new regulations came into force and are considering whether to adjust their payments to bring them in line with the amended PIP regulations.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","68941","2017-03-28T14:16:17.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713583/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713583/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713583/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-23","Personal Independence Payment: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people with mental health conditions who will be affected by the changes to personal independence payments in the Social Security (Personal Independence Payment) (Amendment) Regulations 2017.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","68940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713584","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-28","<p>Recent changes to the Personal Independence Payment (PIP) regulations clarify the original criteria used to decide how much benefit claimants receive. This is not a policy change, nor is it intended to make new savings. It will not result in any claimants, regardless of their health condition, seeing a reduction in the amount of PIP previously awarded by DWP.</p><p> </p><p>We are aware of a small number of cases, around 50 cases currently, where people may have been awarded a higher level of PIP by a tribunal. This could occur if their case was heard at appeal and a tribunal made a higher award, applying the rulings of the Upper Tribunal. We will not be claiming back the money these individuals received during the period before the new regulations came into force and are considering whether to adjust their payments to bring them in line with the amended PIP regulations.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","68940","2017-03-28T14:16:17.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713584/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713584/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713584/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-23","Personal Independence Payment: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who have been awarded the highest rate of personal independence payment solely on the basis of a mental health condition will be affected by the changes to that payment in the Social Security (Personal Independence Payment) (Amendment) Regulations 2017.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","68941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713585","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-31","<p>Imposing a sanction is not something we do lightly. Claimants are given every opportunity to explain why they failed to meet their agreed conditionality requirements, before a decision is made.</p><p> </p><p>A sanction reduces a claimant’s Universal Credit award by an amount never more than their standard allowance element entitlement.</p><p> </p><p>A claimant with a health condition or disability, who makes a claim for Universal Credit on or after 3 April 2017, and who is found to have limited capability for work following a WCA, will not be eligible for the limited capability for work element of Universal Credit.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","68901","2017-03-31T11:48:55.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713585/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713585/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713585/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-23","Universal Credit: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, in what set of circumstances a person would receive a sanction equal to the financial support they receive from universal credit.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","68957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713586","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-28","<p>DWP is committed to valuing equality and diversity. The Equality Act 2010 is embedded into all DWP Processes and Policies. However, there is no requirement to publish evidence of Equality Analysis undertaken.</p><p> </p><p>Evidence of Equality Analysis undertaken within DWP is not centrally collated and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-28T14:59:28.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713586/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713586/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-23","Equality: Impact Assessments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 14 March 2017 to Question 66566, if he will set out each case in the current Parliamentary session for which an equalities impact assessment has been produced but not published; and in each of those cases the reason for non-publication.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","69020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713587","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-28","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>A decision is made on a case-by-case basis on whether or not to cease DLA payments to claimants who do not register for PIP within the allowed time. Additional support is provided for those claimants identified as ‘vulnerable’ (i.e. mental health or learning disabilities) who do not respond to the PIP invite letter.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-28T14:22:52.71Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713587/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713587/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713587/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-23","Disability Living Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many eligible disability living allowance (DLA) claimants have been invited to apply for personal independence payments since April 2016; and of those claimants invited to apply, how many have not applied within the time allowed and have had their DLA terminated as a result.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","69022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713588","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-29","<p>The Department continuously looks for opportunities to improve the PIP claims process.</p><p> </p><p>As part of that, we are carrying out a small-scale pilot to test whether there are any benefits to audio recording face-to-face assessments.</p><p> </p><p>The pilot only began recently, on March 13; once the results have been processed and evaluated, we will be better placed to assess the efficacy of audio recording PIP assessments.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-29T15:32:35.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713588/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713588/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713588/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-23","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the efficacy of the use of cassette audio recording equipment during personal independence payment assessments.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","69041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713589","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-29","<p>The independent Matthew Taylor review on employment practices in a modern economy is considering the impact of non-standard working arrangements on employment status and employment rights. That review will be reporting in the summer with recommendations which this Government will consider.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-29T14:48:28.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713589/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713589/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713589/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-23","Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, following the independent self-employment review of February 2016, whether he plans to introduce a legal definition of self-employment.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","69019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713590","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-29","<p>The Government will consult in the summer on whether there is a case for greater parity in parental benefits between the employed and the self-employed.</p><p> </p><p>Local Authorities may make a payment equivalent to Maternity Allowance in cases where adopters do not qualify for family related statutory pay because they are self-employed. This payment is discretionary and means-tested to ensure that resources are targeted at those adopters who need it most and is part of a package of post-adoption support.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-29T14:52:01.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713590/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713590/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713590/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-23","Adoption: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, following the independent self-employment review of February 2016, what steps he is taking to introduce a new adoption allowance for self-employed people.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","69018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713591","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Government has recently announced that it will consult in the summer on whether there is a case for greater parity in parental benefits between the employed and the self-employed. We are in the process of considering the scope of the consultation, which will include Maternity Allowance.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-28T16:10:04.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713591/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713591/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713591/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-23","Maternity Allowance: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, following the independent self-employment review of February 2016, what steps he is taking to enhance the level of maternity allowance for self-employed people.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","69017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713593","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-29","<p>Entitlement to statutory employment rights, including family related statutory leave and pay, is determined by the individual’s employment status and not the type of contract that they have. This means that many women on casual, fixed-term or zero-hours contracts will already enjoy the same maternity benefits as women in full-time, permanent employment.</p><p>The wide ranging independent review of Modern Employment Practices is looking at the impact of non-standard forms of employment on security, pay and rights</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-29T13:06:14.79Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713593/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713593/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713593/answer","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713593/answer/previousversion/42702","Biography information for Margot James","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-23","Conditions of Employment: Maternity Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of applying equivalent maternity rights for women in permanent employment to women in casual, fixed-term or zero-hours employment contracts.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","68999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713594","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-30","<p>The Government has examined the Commission’s impact assessment and has carried out its own call for views in order to gather evidence from interested parties. The Government has also held a number of meetings with various sectors of industry, including roundtable meetings which I have hosted. The negotiations are still at an early stage and the Government is engaging with stakeholders to ensure that the copyright system works in the interests of UK creative and digital businesses.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-03-30T15:02:30.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713594/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713594/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713594/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-23","Copyright: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of proposed changes to EU copyright law on UK firms engaged in the digital economy.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","68990"
