"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713060","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-03-24","<p>The Government is conducting analysis at the macroeconomic and sectoral level to understand the impact of leaving the EU on all aspects of the UK, including the agriculture sector. We want our new partnership with the EU to allow for tariff free trade in goods and to minimise the regulatory and market access barriers for both goods and services.</p><p>We have recently heard from the International Meat Trade Association, National Farmers’ Union, and the National Pig Association, and have held a number of ministerial roundtables on this subject.</p><p>We have however been clear that we are not going to publish anything that might risk harming our negotiating position.</p><p><strong></strong><br><br></p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-03-24T14:38:10.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713060/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713060/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-21","Agriculture: Export Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of tariff increases on the viability of the UK agriculture industry sector in the event that the UK leaves the single market.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","68720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713061","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-03-29","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given on 22 March 2017 to the Question 68043. The Cabinet Office publishes FOI statistics on behalf of the whole of the government. FOI statistics do not refer to requests responded to within 30 days as the statutory deadline is 20 days.</p><p>FOI statistics are Official Statistics and are governed by the standards set out by the UK Statistics Authority (UKSA) in their Code of Practice. To publish information outside of the release timetable would be a breach of Protocol 2 of the Code of Practice for Official Statistics.<br><br>The latest Freedom of Information statistics were published in December 2016 and are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/freedom-of-information-statistics-july-to-september-2016--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/freedom-of-information-statistics-july-to-september-2016--2</a> <strong><br></strong></p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-03-29T10:28:52.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713061/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713061/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-21","Department for Exiting the European Union: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, on how many occasions his Department took longer than 30 working days to respond to a freedom of information request in each month since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","68668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713086","Department of Health","false","2017-03-28","<p>It is not possible to detect every condition in every pregnancy at screening before 24 weeks of gestation. A screening test is not diagnostic; some conditions may subsequently be detected either at clinical ultrasound examination later in pregnancy, at birth or in the early postnatal period.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-03-28T13:28:17.97Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713086/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713086/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-21","Congenital Abnormalities","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord O’Shaughnessy on 20 March (HL5811), why they do not maintain a list of foetal anomalies that cannot be identified before 24 weeks gestation.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713087","Department of Health","false","2017-03-29","<p>An Expert Working Group of the Commission on Human Medicines is conducting a comprehensive scientific review on the evidence for a possible causal association between Hormone Pregnancy Tests (HPTs), including Primodos, and birth defects. Any important new evidence identified in the Sky News documentary will be reviewed by the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency and provided to the Expert Working Group for their consideration and advice.</p><p> </p><p>While the evidence for any association between HPTs and congenital defects is still under consideration it would be premature to comment on the need for a public inquiry.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is not providing any funding to researchers in Cambridge or Aberdeen who are examining the composition of the drug Primodos and its likely effects on the child in the womb.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL6208","2017-03-29T14:44:21.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713087/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713087/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-21","Primodos","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the Sky News documentary <i>Primodos: The Secret Drugs Scandal</i>; and whether they will consider establishing a public inquiry into the alleged failure of the regulator at that time to protect public safety.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713088","Department of Health","false","2017-03-29","<p>An Expert Working Group of the Commission on Human Medicines is conducting a comprehensive scientific review on the evidence for a possible causal association between Hormone Pregnancy Tests (HPTs), including Primodos, and birth defects. Any important new evidence identified in the Sky News documentary will be reviewed by the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency and provided to the Expert Working Group for their consideration and advice.</p><p> </p><p>While the evidence for any association between HPTs and congenital defects is still under consideration it would be premature to comment on the need for a public inquiry.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is not providing any funding to researchers in Cambridge or Aberdeen who are examining the composition of the drug Primodos and its likely effects on the child in the womb.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL6207","2017-03-29T14:44:21.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713088/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713088/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-21","Primodos","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what funding they are providing to researchers based in (1) Cambridge, and (2) Aberdeen, who are examining the composition of the drug Primodos and its likely effects on the child in the womb.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713089","Home Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>The Government takes the welfare of detainees extremely seriously and has carefully considered the HM Chief Inspector of Prison’s (HMCIP) report on Morton Hall immigration removal centre. The service improvement plan will be published on the HMCIP website shortly.</p><p> </p><p>We will closely monitor progress towards implementing these recommendations. Stephen Shaw CBE has been invited to carry out a short review later this year to assess progress against his previous review into the welfare in detention of vulnerable persons.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL6210","2017-04-03T10:46:49.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713089/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713089/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-21","Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the <i>Report on an unannounced inspection of Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre</i> by HM Chief Inspector of Prisons, published on 21 March.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713090","Home Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>The Government takes the welfare of detainees extremely seriously and has carefully considered the HM Chief Inspector of Prison’s (HMCIP) report on Morton Hall immigration removal centre. The service improvement plan will be published on the HMCIP website shortly.</p><p> </p><p>We will closely monitor progress towards implementing these recommendations. Stephen Shaw CBE has been invited to carry out a short review later this year to assess progress against his previous review into the welfare in detention of vulnerable persons.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL6209","2017-04-03T10:46:49.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713090/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713090/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713090/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-21","Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their response to the findings of the <i>Report on an unannounced inspection of Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre</i> by HM Chief Inspector of Prisons, published on 21 March, in particular that (1) too many detainees were held for prolonged periods, (2) the average length of detention was high, (3) children were detained for long periods of time due to failures in age assessment processes, (4) in one case, an incorrect Home Office age assessment led to the detention of a child for 36 days before social services confirmed that the boy was 16 years old, (5) the adults at risk policy was not yet widely understood, (6) there had been a three-fold increase in incidents of self-harm since the previous inspection, (7) the causes of self-harm had not been sufficiently analysed and there was no strategy to reduce it, and (8) four detainees had narrowly escaped fatal or serious injuries as a result of self-harm during the previous year.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713091","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-04","<p>No Personal Independence Payment (PIP) claimants will see a reduction in the amount of PIP previously awarded by the Department for Work and Pensions as a result of the regulations being introduced, including the point at which their claim is next reviewed.</p><p> </p><p>We are aware of a small number of cases, where people may have been awarded a higher level of PIP by a tribunal. This could occur if their case was heard at appeal and a tribunal made a higher award, applying the rulings of the Upper Tribunal. We will not be claiming back the money these individuals received during the period before the new regulations came into force and are considering whether to adjust their payments to bring them in line with the amended PIP regulations.</p><p> </p><p>I will place a copy of the Equality Impact Assessment in the House Library.</p>",,"Lord Henley","HL6212 ; HL6213","2017-04-04T14:40:06.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713091/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713091/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-21","Personal Independence Payment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the number of people currently receiving the enhanced mobility rate of Personal Independence Payment who will move to the standard rate following their next reassessment, following changes brought forward in the Social Security (Personal Independence Payment) (Amendment) Regulations 2017; and what assessment they have made of the impact of that change on those individuals.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hollins",,"Baroness Hollins","HL6211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713092","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-04","<p>No Personal Independence Payment (PIP) claimants will see a reduction in the amount of PIP previously awarded by the Department for Work and Pensions as a result of the regulations being introduced, including the point at which their claim is next reviewed.</p><p> </p><p>We are aware of a small number of cases, where people may have been awarded a higher level of PIP by a tribunal. This could occur if their case was heard at appeal and a tribunal made a higher award, applying the rulings of the Upper Tribunal. We will not be claiming back the money these individuals received during the period before the new regulations came into force and are considering whether to adjust their payments to bring them in line with the amended PIP regulations.</p><p> </p><p>I will place a copy of the Equality Impact Assessment in the House Library.</p>",,"Lord Henley","HL6211 ; HL6213","2017-04-04T14:40:07.15Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713092/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713092/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713092/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-21","Personal Independence Payment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the number of people currently receiving the enhanced mobility rate of Personal Independence Payment who will not be entitled to receive any mobility rate following their next reassessment, following changes brought forward in the Social Security (Personal Independence Payment) (Amendment) Regulations 2017; and what assessment they have made of the impact of that change on those individuals.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hollins",,"Baroness Hollins","HL6212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713093","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-04","<p>No Personal Independence Payment (PIP) claimants will see a reduction in the amount of PIP previously awarded by the Department for Work and Pensions as a result of the regulations being introduced, including the point at which their claim is next reviewed.</p><p> </p><p>We are aware of a small number of cases, where people may have been awarded a higher level of PIP by a tribunal. This could occur if their case was heard at appeal and a tribunal made a higher award, applying the rulings of the Upper Tribunal. We will not be claiming back the money these individuals received during the period before the new regulations came into force and are considering whether to adjust their payments to bring them in line with the amended PIP regulations.</p><p> </p><p>I will place a copy of the Equality Impact Assessment in the House Library.</p>",,"Lord Henley","HL6211 ; HL6212","2017-04-04T14:40:07.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713093/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713093/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713093/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-21","Personal Independence Payment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the number of people currently receiving the standard mobility rate of Personal Independence Payment who will not be entitled to receive any mobility rate following their next reassessment, following changes brought forward in the Social Security (Personal Independence Payment) (Amendment) Regulations 2017; and what assessment they have made of the impact of that change on those individuals.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hollins",,"Baroness Hollins","HL6213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713094","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-04","<p>The table below provides an estimate of the number of people with the conditions requested currently receiving Personal Independence Payment who satisfied descriptors c, d or f of mobility activity 1 at the point of original decision by the Department. Information on the numbers following mandatory reconsideration or appeal is not available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Mobility Activity 1: descriptors c, d or f</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Anxiety / Depressive Disorders</p></td><td><p>4,700</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bipolar Affective Disorder</p></td><td><p>1,500</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Depressive Disorder</p></td><td><p>2,400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Personality Disorder</p></td><td><p>1,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Post Traumatic Stress Disorder</p></td><td><p>600</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Schizophrenia and Schizoaffective disorder</p></td><td><p>5,200</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Notes: Figures rounded to the nearest 100</p><p>Figures are at 31 January 2017</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2017-04-04T15:25:05.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713094/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713094/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-21","Personal Independence Payment: Mental Illness","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the number of people with each of (1) anxiety and depressive disorders, (2) depressive disorder, (3) schizophrenia, (4) bipolar affective disorder, (5) personality disorder, (6) post traumatic stress disorder, or other psychotic disorders who currently receive the Personal Independence Payment and who at their original assessment (or following mandatory reconsideration or appeal) scored points by satisfying descriptors 1c, 1d and 1f of the mobility component.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hollins",,"Baroness Hollins","HL6214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713095","Cabinet Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>The Government believes that the independent Advisory Committee on Business Appointments discharges its remit effectively and efficiently.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-04-03T14:11:51.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713095/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713095/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-21","Business Appointments Advisory Committee","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will review the effectiveness of the Advisory Committee on Business Appointments.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL6215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713096","Department for Education","false","2017-03-28","<p>As announced at the Spending Review, we will be removing the Education Services Grant general funding rate from 2017-18. We recognise that local authorities will need support with this change, which is why we have introduced a new transitional grant worth £125m in 2017-18. We have also amended regulations to allow local authorities to use other sources of funding to pay for education services for maintained schools once the ESG is removed from September 2017. Local authorities are allowed to retain some of their maintained schools’ Dedicated Schools Grant so that they can continue to deliver the statutory duties they carry out on behalf of maintained schools previously funded through the Education Services Grant general funding rate.</p><p>If local authorities cannot agree with their maintained schools on the level of funding to retain, local authorities have recourse to the Secretary of State.</p><p>Funding delivered through the ESG retained duties rate, which funds duties that local authorities hold in respect of all schools, is not being removed. In 2017-18, this funding has been moved into the Dedicated Schools Grant and paid to local authorities on a per-pupil basis. From 2018-19, this funding will be allocated to local authorities through the central school services block.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-03-28T16:15:13.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713096/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713096/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713096/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-21","Schools: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the warning from the Local Government Association that reductions in the central government-provided education services grant may result in some local authorities potentially being unable to meet legal obligations to schools, such as checking staff for criminal records and ensuring that buildings are free of asbestos, what recourse is available to affected pupils, parents, school staff and other local residents if those legal obligations are not met.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL6216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713097","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-04","<p>Non-executive members of the Channel 4 Corporation board are appointed by Ofcom with the approval of the Secretary of State. Ofcom advertised for four vacancies for candidates with specific sector skills and experience. The Secretary of State approved the four candidates on the basis that they met the skills and experience set out in the advertised job descriptions.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde","HL6218","2017-04-04T11:35:30.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713097/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713097/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-21","Channel Four Television: Public Appointments","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ashton of Hyde on 21 March (HL5834), whether the female candidate who was not approved for appointment by the Secretary of State failed to meet the skills and experience set out in the advertised job descriptions; and if so, whether they have determined that Ofcom was wrong to recommend her as suitably qualified to be appointed.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL6217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713098","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-04","<p>Non-executive members of the Channel 4 Corporation board are appointed by Ofcom with the approval of the Secretary of State. Ofcom advertised for four vacancies for candidates with specific sector skills and experience. The Secretary of State approved the four candidates on the basis that they met the skills and experience set out in the advertised job descriptions.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde","HL6217","2017-04-04T11:35:30.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713098/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713098/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-21","Channel Four Television: Public Appointments","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ashton of Hyde on 21 March (HL5834), whether the reason why the female candidate who was not approved for appointment by the Secretary of State was that the Department for Culture, Media and Sport targets of 50 per cent and 10 per cent for female and BAME candidates, respectively, had already been exceeded, that the female candidate was from a minority ethnic background, whereas the successful four men appointed were not, or for some other reason.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL6218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713099","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>​The UK does not endorse the Economic and Social Commission for Western Asia report. The British Government has not engaged the UN in discussions about the report, and it has been withdrawn by the UN.</p><p>The situation on the ground demonstrates the urgent need to make progress towards peace. The UK remains committed to the two-state solution as the best way to bring peace and stability to the region.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-03T16:07:49.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713099/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713099/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-21","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had at the UN regarding the report by the UN Economic and Social Commission for Western Asia which stated that Israel practises apartheid against Palestine.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL6219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713100","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>We have not raised this issue with Israeli authorities.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-03T16:08:37.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713100/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713100/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-21","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of reports of the shooting of Ibrahim Mahmoud Matar by the Israeli police on 13 March, what representations they are making to the government of Israel regarding the killing of Palestinian suspects who have already been detained.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL6220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713101","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>Yes, we have received a report on this issue from our Consulate-General in Jerusalem.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-03T16:08:51.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713101/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713101/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713101/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-21","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have received reports of tear gas and rubber bullets being used in schools in Abu Dis in March.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL6221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713102","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>The Minister for the Middle East and Africa raised this issue with the Israeli Ambassador to London on 1 March. Officials from our Embassy in Tel Aviv also regularly raised this issue with the Israeli authorities, most recently on 9 March 2017. We welcomed progress made in recent Israeli policy amendments.</p><p>However, the UK continues to have strong concerns about continued reports of ill-treatment of Palestinian minors. Embassy officials meet with the Israeli authorities on a regular basis to advocate for the end of night-time arrests and summons, consistent access to lawyers and parents for all minors, and implementation of other protection measures.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-03T16:09:44.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713102/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713102/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-21","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what recent representations they have made to the government of Israel about the treatment of Palestinian child prisoners; and what assessment they have made of whether that treatment has improved during the last year.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL6222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713103","Department of Health","false","2017-03-28","<p>The recording of a patient’s marital status on the HSA4 abortion notification forms is a requirement set out in the Abortion (Amendment) (England) Regulations 2002.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-03-28T13:23:50.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713103/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713103/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713103/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-21","Abortion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answers by Lord O’Shaughnessy on 21 March (HL5804 and HL5905), why a patient's marital status, where known, is requested on HSA4 abortion notification forms.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL6223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713104","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-04","<p>The Government strongly supports the need to provide more employment opportunities to adults with a learning disability or autism.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015 3,140 individuals with a learning disability started the Work Choice programme, with 61% achieving a job outcome. 2016 annual data are not yet available. In 2015 the department introduced Specialist Employability Support (SES) to provide up to a further 1700 places per year intensive and personalised support for people, including those with learning disabilities.</p><p> </p><p>Disability Confident works to influence employers to take on more disabled people, including those with learning disabilities, and to market Access to Work to disabled people.</p><p> </p><p>Access to Work has a new Hidden Impairment Support Team which aims to give advice and guidance to employers, and offers eligible workers an assessment of their needs at work and a support plan.</p><p> </p><p>Last year, Paul Maynard MP led a taskforce that made recommendations to Government on how to improve access to apprenticeships for people with learning disabilities. Department for Work and Pensions and the Department for Education are working together to implement all of these recommendations.</p><p> </p><p>Looking forward, we are testing ways to improve our support for people with learning disabilities through a Local Supported Employment proof of concept and Supported Work Experience for young people, which offers young people with learning disabilities and other long term conditions a chance to spend time with an employer.</p><p><strong></strong></p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2017-04-04T14:23:16.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713104/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713104/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713104/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-21","Employment: Learning Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to encourage the full-time employment of adults with special learning needs; and what progress was made in (1) 2015, and (2) 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Condon",,"Lord Condon","HL6224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713105","Department of Health","false","2017-03-29","<p>Improving the oral health of young children is a Public Health England (PHE) priority. PHE’s Child Oral Health Improvement Programme Board provides national system leadership for the delivery of the shared ambition that every child grows up free of tooth decay as part of getting the best start in life.</p><p> </p><p>The two key actions to prevent tooth decay are reducing sugar consumption and getting fluoride onto teeth which can be by means of fluoride toothpaste, fluoride varnish and water fluoridation. PHE has published a number of toolkits to support local authorities in improving child oral health.</p><p> </p><p>In addition the Government’s Childhood Obesity Plan, launched in August 2016, contained proposals for a broad, structured sugar reduction programme to remove sugar from the categories of food that contribute the most to children’s sugar intakes. The Government also announced the Soft Drinks Industry Levy last year, which will apply from April 2018.</p><p> </p><p>To support families to reduce their sugar intake, PHE’s Change4Life launched the Be Food Smart campaign in January 2017 which encourages families to download the app which reveals the amount of sugar, saturated fat and salt in food and drink.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-03-29T14:45:11.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713105/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713105/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713105/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-21","Dental Health: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to prevent tooth decay in children under the age of five, in the light of the increase in tooth extractions in England in the last ten years.","false","Biography information for Lord Condon",,"Lord Condon","HL6225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713106","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-30","<p>Our statement reflects the conclusion of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change Fifth Assessment Report that it is virtually certain (&gt;99% probability) that natural internal variability alone cannot account for the observed increase in global surface temperatures. This statement is based on computer model simulations, which capture both the observed magnitude and spatial patterns of warming only when both human and natural forcings are included. Further, reconstructions of past climate variability from records such as ice cores also reveal that recent temperature changes are clearly distinct from natural variability. These records show that temperatures over the last 50 years in the Northern Hemisphere (where records of past climate are most comprehensive) were unusually high relative to the last 1000 years.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-03-30T14:16:31.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713106/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713106/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713106/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-21","Climate Change","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 14 March (HL5780), whether their statement that the increase in global average surface temperatures is not consistent with natural internal variability is supported by evidence that is not based upon computer simulation of the climate.","false","Biography information for Lord Donoughue",,"Lord Donoughue","HL6226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713107","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-04","<p>We constantly review and monitor the size of the Civil Service workforce to meet the Prime Minister’s priorities.<br><br>The Chancellor of the Exchequer announced £412m of additional funding to support EU exit and trade policy. The Civil Service is focused on delivering the Government’s commitment to leave the European Union and get the very best deal for the UK. We are equipping ourselves with the right people and the right skills across government to make this happen, and keeping our plans - and ability to deliver them - under constant review. <br><br></p><p><strong><p><p><p><br></strong></p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2017-04-04T15:36:59.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713107/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713107/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713107/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-21","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that they have the necessary resources to manage the transition of powers from the EU, in relation to (1) central government departments, and (2) assessing and managing the impact of leaving the EU on the devolution settlements.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL6227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713108","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>The Government understands the hardship that lack of pension payments causes to former service-people and their families. The British Ambassador to Zimbabwe raises pensions frequently with the Zimbabwean Government and has secured written confirmation that it will resume payments when the economic situation improves. However, we have not made an estimate of the cost as these payments are the responsibility of the Government of Zimbabwe as set out in the Lancaster House Agreement in 1979.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-03T16:10:24.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713108/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713108/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713108/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-21","Zimbabwe: Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the cost of making the necessary financial arrangements to enable the government of Zimbabwe to pay the pension arrears owing to those former members of HM Overseas Service who responded to the British Government's request that they remain in their posts after Southern Rhodesia became independent.","true","Biography information for Lord Goodlad",,"Lord Goodlad","HL6228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713109","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-03","<p>The number of instances of fly-tipping reported by local authorities, and the number of successful prosecutions brought over the last three years are set out in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year</p></td><td><p>Number of Incidents</p></td><td><p>Number of successful prosecutions</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>852,036</p></td><td><p>1,953</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>899,763</p></td><td><p>1,771</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>936,090</p></td><td><p>2,091</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The data is published on the GOV.UK website.</p><p> </p><p>The overall trend in fly-tipping incidents had shown a steady decline between 2007/08 and 2012/13 until 2013/14 when there was an increase to 852,000 incidents. Prosecutions have been more variable, with a peak in 2011/12. The 2015/16 figure is more average.</p><p> </p><p>Many local authorities have started to improve the way they capture and report fly-tips over the past few years, so the increase over time should be interpreted with some care. It has also been brought to our attention that the definitions used to describe fly-tips are interpreted broadly from the guidance.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-04-03T16:05:17.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713109/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713109/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713109/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-21","Fly-tipping","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many instances of fly tipping have been reported in each of the past three financial years; and how many successful prosecutions have been brought over the same period.","false","Biography information for Viscount Goschen",,"Viscount Goschen","HL6229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713110","Home Office","false","2017-03-30","<p>The Home Office does not hold the requested information centrally.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Statistics on theft or unauthorised taking of a motor vehicle, which will include motorcycles, are regularly published by the Office for National Statistics. This can be found in Table A4 of the latest Crime in England and Wales publication.</p><p> </p><p>Information on prosecutions is the responsibility of the Ministry of Justice. They have informed us that they do not hold the requested data.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-03-30T15:19:01.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713110/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713110/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713110/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-21","Motorcycles: Theft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many instances of motorcycle theft have been reported in each of the past three financial years; and how many successful prosecutions have been brought over the same period.","false","Biography information for Viscount Goschen",,"Viscount Goschen","HL6230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713111","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>​Travel advice is kept under constant review. Risk to British nationals is our foremost consideration. The advice for each country is varied to reflect local conditions: there are two categories of overall advice in Tunisia, three in Lebanon plus detailed and specific guidance for each.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-03T16:10:57.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713111/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713111/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713111/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-21","Lebanon and Tunisia: Travel Information","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they will review their travel advice for (1) Tunisia, and (2) Lebanon, in the light of the economic development and democratic progress made by those countries; and what assessment they have made of the appropriateness of issuing blanket guidance for the whole of each country.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL6231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713112","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>The UK supports the moderate opposition in Syria, which has repeatedly underlined its commitment to a negotiated political settlement in line with international agreements. We recognise that the brutality of the Syrian regime has been the primary driver of extremism and terrorism in Syria. In the long term, therefore, terrorism and extremism can only be sustainably defeated in Syria through a political transition.</p><p>We provide certain groups in the moderate opposition with political and practical support so that they can stand up to both the tyranny of Asad and that of Daesh. This has included communications, medical and logistics equipment and equipment to protect against chemical weapons attacks. The UK does not provide weapons to anybody in Syria. We will maintain this support, while continually and rigorously assessing all recipients to ensure that they are not involved in any extremist activity or human rights abuses.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-03T16:11:58.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713112/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713112/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713112/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-21","Syria: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 20 March (HL Deb 10), whether they will cease giving political and practical support to armed insurgent groups in Syria in the interests of promoting the expulsion of Daesh from that country.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL6232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713113","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>This Government recognises the importance of free movement of journalists to cover issues of global importance. This must be balanced against security and safety considerations. The Government currently advises against all travel to Yemen.</p><p>The Foreign Secretary last spoke to the Saudi Arabian Foreign Minister, Adel al Jubeir on 22 March and discussed the importance of finding progress towards a political settlement.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-03T16:12:32.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713113/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713113/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713113/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-21","Yemen: Press Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Saudi Arabia regarding enabling journalists to enter Yemen.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL6233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713114","Home Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>The Home Office does not comment on individual cases.</p><p>The Home Office policy is not to detain children. Where there is doubt as to the age of an individual. Immigration Enforcement will detain individuals who claim to be a child (under 18) until they are referred to a local authority for a Morton-compliant age assessment. Individuals who frustrate the age assessment and identification process may incur a lengthened period of detention. All three individuals were later identified as children and released into the custody of local authorities.</p><p>The Government will respond to HM Chief Inspector of Prisons Report on the unannounced inspection of Morton Hall immigration Removal Centre in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-04-03T12:19:12.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713114/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713114/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713114/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-21","Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the <i>Report on an unannounced inspection of Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre</i> by HM Chief Inspector of Prisons, published on 21 March, what assessment they have made of the reasons for children being detained at the centre for (1) 12 days, (2) 36 days, and (3) 151 days, during the last year.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL6234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713115","Home Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>It is already the case that individuals detained under Immigration Act powers are held for the minimum time necessary to achieve their removal from the United Kingdom.<strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>As part of the Government’s response to the review of the welfare in detention of vulnerable persons undertaken by Stephen Shaw CBE the Home Office has introduced, or is planning to introduce, a range of measure designed to further minimise the length of time individuals spend in immigration detention. These measures include: a new internal detention gatekeeper function to monitor admissions to the detention estate; new case progression plans with a clear focus on the individual’s removal from the UK; and quarterly internal case progression panels to monitor progression of all detained cases and reduce the number of long-term detainees. <br></p><p>The Government has no plans to introduce a maximum time limit on immigration detention.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-04-03T10:40:36.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713115/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713115/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713115/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-21","Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the <i>Report on an unannounced inspection of Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre</i> by HM Chief Inspector of Prisons, published on 21 March, what steps they are taking to reduce the length of time individuals are detained; and whether they plan to introduce a maximum length of detention.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL6235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713116","Home Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>Any individual detained within immigration detention is already subject to regular review, both on a scheduled basis and whenever there is any change in circumstances that might be material to the decision on whether or not to continue detention. Reviews are carried out at successively more senior levels the longer the detention continues.</p><p> </p><p>Following publication of the Government’s response to Stephen Shaw’s Report into the welfare in detention of vulnerable persons on 14 January 2016, work has been ongoing to design a more effective case management process to replace the existing procedure for reviewing detention. This includes a more proactive approach to the review of detention, through Case Progression Plans which show the monitoring and review of ongoing detention and with a focus on return or, if appropriate, release. Case Progression Plans are currently being piloted across the Home Office and are subject to evaluation.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-04-03T12:20:22.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713116/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713116/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713116/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-21","Immigrants: Detainees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress they have made in introducing detention reviews for those held in immigration removal centres.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL6236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713117","Home Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>We are currently working with the Ministry of Justice, Her Majesty’s Court Service and the First-tier Tribunal to implement the Secretary of State’s duty to introduce automatic bail hearings, as set out in paragraph 11 of Schedule 10 to the Immigration Act 2016. This is one of a number of reforms necessary to implement the wider immigration bail provisions in Schedule 10 and it will be commenced alongside those other provisions in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-04-03T10:39:07.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713117/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713117/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713117/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-21","Immigration Bail","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they intend to introduce automatic bail hearings under Schedule 10 to the Immigration Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL6237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713118","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-05","<p>This government has made a clear commitment to protect workers’ rights, and ensure that they keep pace with the changing labour market as we leave the EU. Furthermore, we do not need to be part of the EU to have strong protections for workers' rights - the UK already goes beyond EU minimum standards in a number of areas.</p><p>Both DExEU Ministers and senior officials have met a wide range of interested organisations to hear concerns and gather insight. So far, the Secretary of State, the Permanent Secretary, and DExEU officials have met the TUC, and the Secretary of State has met UNISON. This engagement will continue as we move into the negotiation phase of our exit from the EU and will help to inform our negotiating positions.</p><p>Details of Ministerial meetings, and those of senior officials, will be published in the Department’s Quarterly Transparency Returns, which will be made publicly available on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL6240","2017-04-05T15:49:51.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713118/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713118/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713118/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-21","Conditions of Employment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that the interests of UK workers are taken into account during Article 50 negotiations.","false","Biography information for Lord Monks",,"Lord Monks","HL6238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713119","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-04","<p>The Government remains committed to protecting and enhancing workers’ rights following the UK’s exit from the EU. All employment rights which currently apply in the UK, including those derived from EU law, will continue to be guaranteed after exit. The Great Repeal Bill will provide the mechanism for this.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-04-04T11:29:20.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713119/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713119/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713119/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-21","Conditions of Employment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to transpose into UK legislation, both pre- and post-Brexit, all European employment rights.","false","Biography information for Lord Monks",,"Lord Monks","HL6239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713120","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-05","<p>This government has made a clear commitment to protect workers’ rights, and ensure that they keep pace with the changing labour market as we leave the EU. Furthermore, we do not need to be part of the EU to have strong protections for workers' rights - the UK already goes beyond EU minimum standards in a number of areas.</p><p>Both DExEU Ministers and senior officials have met a wide range of interested organisations to hear concerns and gather insight. So far, the Secretary of State, the Permanent Secretary, and DExEU officials have met the TUC, and the Secretary of State has met UNISON. This engagement will continue as we move into the negotiation phase of our exit from the EU and will help to inform our negotiating positions.</p><p>Details of Ministerial meetings, and those of senior officials, will be published in the Department’s Quarterly Transparency Returns, which will be made publicly available on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL6238","2017-04-05T15:49:51.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713120/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713120/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713120/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-21","Conditions of Employment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they intend to involve the TUC and trade unions in the Article 50 negotiations.","false","Biography information for Lord Monks",,"Lord Monks","HL6240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713121","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-29","<p>In spring 2015, the European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) launched a preliminary in-flight cabin air measurement campaign, which will develop a methodology, and put into place adequate equipment to perform cockpit and cabin air measurements.</p><p> </p><p>The results of this campaign, which will be used to prepare for an envisaged large scale project in the future, were published on 23 March 2017. The results show that the cabin/cockpit air quality is similar or better than what is observed in normal indoor environments. No occupational exposure limits and guidelines were exceeded.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-03-29T10:43:35.533Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713121/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713121/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713121/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-21","Aircraft: Air Conditioning","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect the European Aviation Safety Agency to publish its report on cabin air quality, commissioned in 2015.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL6241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713122","Home Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>As part of the Government’s response to the review of the welfare in detention of vulnerable persons undertaken by Stephen Shaw CBE the Home Office has introduced, or is planning to introduce, a range of measures designed to further minimise the length of time individuals spend in immigration detention. These include: a new internal detention gatekeeper function to monitor admissions to the detention estate; new case progression plans with a clear focus on the individual’s removal from the UK; and quarterly internal case progression panels to monitor progression of all detained cases and reduce the number of long-term detainees.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-04-03T10:41:42.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713122/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713122/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713122/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-21","Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the <i>Report on an unannounced inspection of Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre</i> by HM Chief Inspector of Prisons, published on 21 March, what steps they are taking to reduce the length of time individuals are detained for immigration purposes.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL6242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713123","Home Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>The Home Office engages with civil society organisations at official and Ministerial level on a regular basis as part of the development of policy.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-04-03T10:47:58.103Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713123/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713123/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713123/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-21","Immigrants: Detainees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with civil society organisations regarding community-based alternatives to immigration detention centres.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL6243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713124","Home Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>A training presentation pack on Detention Services Order (DSO) on the care and management of adults at risk in the detention estate (08/2016) was circulated to all Home Office Immigration Enforcement staff in the immigration detention estate, including staff at Morton Hall immigration removal centre (IRC) in September 2016.</p><p>The final version of DSO 08/2016 was published on 27 February 2017. Home Office business embedded trainers are delivering training on the DSO to staff in the IRCs, including supplier and healthcare staff. Staff at Morton Hall IRC received training in February and a refresher training session will be added to the annual training schedule for NOMS staff at the centre.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-04-03T10:47:27.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713124/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713124/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713124/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-21","Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the <i>Report on an unannounced inspection of Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre</i> by HM Chief Inspector of Prisons, published on 21 March, what steps they are taking to ensure that staff in immigration detention centres understand and apply their guidance on adults at risk in immigration detention.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL6244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713125","Home Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>All incidents of self harm are treated very seriously and every step is taken to prevent incidents of this nature. Staff at all centres are trained to identify those at risk of self harm so that action can be taken to minimise the risk. Notices in various languages are displayed in IRCs setting out that where a detainee is concerned about a fellow detainee this should be brought to the attention of a member of staff. Formal risk assessments on initial detention and systems for raising concerns at any subsequent point feed into established self harm procedures in every IRC. These are in turn underpinned by the Home Office Operating Standard on the prevention of self-harm and detention services order 06/2008, Assessment Care in Detention Teamwork (ACDT).</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-04-03T10:38:15.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713125/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713125/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713125/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-21","Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, with reference to the <i>Report on an unannounced inspection of Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre</i> by HM Chief Inspector of Prisons, published on 21 March, what assessment they have made of the relationship between the absence of limits on the length of time an individual can be detained and the incidence of self-harm in immigration detention centres.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL6245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713126","Home Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>The Home Secretary and Home Office Ministers conduct visits, and host meetings, on the whole spectrum of Home Office business regularly. It is our policy not to provide details of such visits.</p><p> </p><p>Information on ministers’ meetings is released quarterly as part of Government transparency and accountability data and is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/home-office-ministerial-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-meetings-july-to-september-2016</p><p> </p><p>A copy has also been attached to this answer.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-04-03T10:45:37.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713126/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713126/answer","Copy_of_Ministerial_Template_Final_July-Sep_16__2_ (1).xlsx","Copy_of_Ministerial_Template_Final_July-Sep_16__2_ (1).xlsx","Ministerial Meetings","Ministerial Meetings","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713126/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-21","Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when (1) the Home Secretary, and (2) the Immigration Minister, last visited Morton Hall Immigration Removal Centre.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL6246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713127","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-03","<p>We are clear that violence, self-harm and deaths in our prisons are too high. The department has taken immediate action to stabilise the estate by tackling the drugs, drones and phones that undermine security and are also investing £100m annually to boost the frontline by 2,500 officers. These are long-standing issues that will not be resolved in weeks or months but our wholesale reforms will lay the groundwork to transform our prisons, reduce reoffending and make our communities safer. We will carefully study the details of all deaths in custody to determine whether there are any patterns, or lessons to be learned, to further our understanding of why these tragic events happen. A range of measures will be put in place to help support prisoners who are at risk of self-harm or suicide, especially in the first 24 hours where prisoners are at their most vulnerable. We are also investing more in mental health awareness training for staff.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-04-03T15:57:04.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713127/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713127/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713127/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-21","Prisoners: Suicide","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the increasing annual number of self-inflicted deaths in prisons since 2012, what steps they are taking to reduce the number of such deaths.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL6247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713128","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-30","<p>Allocations for the improved Better Care Fund in 2017-18 (£105 million), 2018-19 (£825 million) and 2019-20 (£1.5 billion) were published (attached) alongside the Local Government Finance Settlement in February 2017 - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/core-spending-power-final-local-government-finance-settlement-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/core-spending-power-final-local-government-finance-settlement-2017-to-2018</a>.</p><p>The additional £2 billion announced at Budget tops up the improved Better Care Fund and the allocations for all three years were published (attached) on 9 March - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-allocations-of-the-additional-funding-for-adult-social-care" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-allocations-of-the-additional-funding-for-adult-social-care</a></p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-03-30T16:27:47.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713128/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713128/answer","170327 additional funding for adult social care - HL6248.xlsx ; 170327 Explanatory note on Core Spending Power - HL6248.pdf","170327 additional funding for adult social care - HL6248.xlsx ; 170327 Explanatory note on Core Spending Power - HL6248.pdf","additional funding for adult social care ; Core Spending Power","additional funding for adult social care ; Core Spending Power","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713128/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-21","Social Services: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 28 December 2016 (HL4038), what allocations from the Better Care Fund will have been made by the end of 2017–18 to each named local authority in England with responsibility for adult social care; and what further resources from this Fund will remain available for distribution in 2018–19 and 2019–20.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL6248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713129","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-04","<p>Council tax levels set by local authorities in England for 2017-18 were published (attached) on 29 March - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/council-tax-levels-set-by-local-authorities-in-england-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/council-tax-levels-set-by-local-authorities-in-england-2017-to-2018</a>.</p><p>In 2017-18, 147 out of 152 adult social care authorities will use some or all of the 3 per cent adult social care precept flexibility when setting their council tax, with 109 using the full, or close to full, 3 per cent. I will place a list of local authorities which will not be using their precept raising power to the maximum permitted level in 2017 -18 to fund adult social care in the House library.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-04-04T16:30:38.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713129/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713129/answer","170329 Council Tax level - HL6249.pdf","170329 Council Tax level - HL6249.pdf","Council Tax Levels Set by local authorities","Council Tax Levels Set by local authorities","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713129/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-21","Social Services: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 23 December 2016 (HL4083), which local authorities in England with responsibility for adult social care will not be using their precept raising power to the maximum permitted level in 2017–18 to fund adult social care.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL6249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713130","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-30","<p>For estimates of the amount that could be raised in 2017-18, I refer to the Department's response to the written question (attached) HL4037 answered on 28 December 2016, which sets out the potential revenue raised for all local authorities - <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Lords/2016-12-12/HL4037/" target="_blank">www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Lords/2016-12-12/HL4037/</a>.</p><p>My department has made no assessment as to (3). Spending Review decisions on social care services took into account a range of financial and economic factors, including projections and data including on the National Living Wage from the Office of Budget Responsibility and Skills for Care.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-03-30T16:26:33.023Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713130/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713130/answer","HL4037.docx","HL4037.docx","Written question - HL4037","Written question - HL4037","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713130/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-21","Social Services: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 23 December 2016 (HL4036), (1) what was the extra amount raised by the social care precept in 2017–18; (2) what is their estimate of the amount that will be raised in 2017–18; and (3) alongside those figures, what are the estimated costs to local authorities for funding the National Living Wage for employees providing adult social care on behalf of local authorities in 2016–17 and 2017–18.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL6250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713131","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-03","<p>No assessment has been made of the implication of the variation in yields for the NHS locally; this is a tax raised and managed by local government, to be spent on adult social care. Our policy on the social care precept has been set until 2019-20. No decision has been made about the policy after 2020.</p><p>The government has taken several steps during this Parliament to help secure a strong and sustainable social care system, including an additional £2 billion of funding announced at Budget to support adult social care in the short term. Taken all together, councils have access to £9.25 billion more dedicated funding for social care over the next three years, as a result of measures introduced by the government since 2015. In the longer term, the government is committed to establishing a fair and more sustainable basis for adult social care, in the face of future demographic challenges, and proposals to put the system on a more secure and sustainable long term footing will be set out in a green paper.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-04-03T14:01:18.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713131/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713131/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713131/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-21","Social Services: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 28 December 2016 (HL4037) and the variation in yield revealed, what assessment they have made of the implications of the variation in yields for the NHS locally; and whether they remain committed to social care precept increases as a basis for funding adult social care on a sustainable basis.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL6251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713132","Department of Health","false","2017-03-28","<p>Information on the number of providers of publicly funded home care and residential and nursing home care services who have handed back contracts is not held centrally. Ministers have received representations from a number of local authorities (LAs) about market fragility which have touched on the risk of and alluded to actual handing back of contracts.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Following the Chancellor’s announcement in the Budget, LAs in England will receive an additional £2 billion for social care over the next three years.</p><p> </p><p>The additional resources will help LAs commission care services that are sustainable, diverse and offer sufficient high quality care and support for people in their areas.</p><p> </p><p>There is a complex relationship between social care and NHS services. NHS England is working with the Department to identify a fuller understanding of the linkages between health and social care services. It is aiming to undertake some detailed work at local level to exploit linked data where it is available to analyse more fully how changes and variation in the provision of social care impacts on health care services.</p><p> </p><p>The results of the best available academic study indicate that for each additional £1 spent on social care, there is a saving to the National Health Service of £0.35. Also, £1 additional NHS spend corresponds to just over £0.35 reduction on social care.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-03-28T13:15:52.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713132/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713132/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713132/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-21","Social Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the number of providers of publicly funded (1) home care, and (2) residential and nursing home care services, who have handed back contracts to local authorities in England; what representations they have received from local authorities and others about this issue; and what assessment they have made of the impact of such actions on the performance of the NHS.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL6252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713133","Department of Health","false","2017-04-04","<p>National Health Service trusts are able to purchase residential and nursing care but we would expect them to do this in a planned way with their local clinical commissioning group and local authority.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-04-04T13:12:20.043Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713133/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713133/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713133/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-21","Care Homes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether NHS hospital trusts are permitted to purchase residential or nursing home beds for patients who no longer need to occupy an acute hospital bed but cannot be discharged to a social care placement.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL6253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713134","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Government commends Cheltenham Borough Council for the steps they have taken which are in line with the Armed Forces Covenant and measures which we have put in place to ensure that serving members of the Armed Forces and veterans are given appropriate priority for social housing.</p><p>In 2012 we introduced regulations to ensure that seriously injured and disabled Service personnel and former members of the Armed Forces with urgent housing needs are always given high priority for social housing.</p><p>At the same time, we introduced regulations to ensure that serving personnel, and veterans who are within 5 years of having been discharged, do not lose their qualification rights for social housing because of the necessity to move from base to base.</p><p>Our 2012 statutory social housing allocations guidance goes further and also strongly encourages councils to take into account the needs of all serving or former Service personnel when framing their housing allocation schemes. It gives examples of how councils can do this, including setting aside a proportion of properties for former members of the Armed Forces under a local lettings policy, which is what Cheltenham Borough Council have done.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-03-28T15:18:31.61Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713134/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713134/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713134/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-21","Housing: Veterans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the initiative by Cheltenham Borough Council to build homes for veterans; and whether they will encourage other local authorities to take similar action to house those who have left the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL6254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713135","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>Although the recent talks have not yet delivered a devolved power-sharing Executive in Northern Ireland, the Government’s priority is to see a functioning Executive in place at Stormont.</p><p> </p><p>Under the devolution settlement, the majority of responsibility for language issues rests with the Northern Ireland Executive, including policy relating to the promotion of minority languages.</p><p> </p><p>As the Government has previously made clear it is committed to affording due respect and parity of esteem to the cultural traditions in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2017-04-03T10:44:33.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713135/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713135/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713135/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-03-21","Irish Language","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the parity of esteem under the 1998 Belfast Agreement, whether any change of status for the Irish language would also be granted to the Ulster Scots language.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL6255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713136","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-04","<p>The government has not yet issued a consultation on making legal services regulators independent from their representative bodies, and will respond to the Competition and Markets Authority’s report and recommendations shortly.</p><p> </p><p>The final report of the Insurance Fraud Task Force (January 2016) included a recommendation that the government should consider strengthening the enforcement powers of the Solicitors Regulation Authority. We are reviewing the position on this and considering what further action may be appropriate.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL6257 ; HL6258 ; HL6259 ; HL6260","2017-04-04T15:48:26.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713136/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713136/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713136/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-21","Legal Profession: Regulation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the consultation proposed in <i>A better deal: boosting competition to bring down bills for families and firms</i> (Cm 9164), published in November 2015, on making legal regulators fully independent of the representative bodies has been launched, and, if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL6256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713137","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-04","<p>The government has not yet issued a consultation on making legal services regulators independent from their representative bodies, and will respond to the Competition and Markets Authority’s report and recommendations shortly.</p><p> </p><p>The final report of the Insurance Fraud Task Force (January 2016) included a recommendation that the government should consider strengthening the enforcement powers of the Solicitors Regulation Authority. We are reviewing the position on this and considering what further action may be appropriate.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL6256 ; HL6258 ; HL6259 ; HL6260","2017-04-04T15:48:27.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713137/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713137/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-21","Legal Profession: Regulation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they plan to consult on making legal regulators fully independent of representative bodies, first proposed in <i>A better deal: boosting competition to bring down bills for families and firms</i> (Cm 9164), published in November 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL6257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713138","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-04","<p>The government has not yet issued a consultation on making legal services regulators independent from their representative bodies, and will respond to the Competition and Markets Authority’s report and recommendations shortly.</p><p> </p><p>The final report of the Insurance Fraud Task Force (January 2016) included a recommendation that the government should consider strengthening the enforcement powers of the Solicitors Regulation Authority. We are reviewing the position on this and considering what further action may be appropriate.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL6256 ; HL6257 ; HL6259 ; HL6260","2017-04-04T15:48:27.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713138/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713138/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713138/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-21","Legal Profession: Regulation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect to respond to the recommendations of the Competition and Markets Authority’s legal services market study report, published on 15 December 2016, and what assessment they have made of the implications of their report regarding the ability for legal regulators to investigate and rule on the ethics, conduct and behaviour of lawyers.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL6258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713139","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-04","<p>The government has not yet issued a consultation on making legal services regulators independent from their representative bodies, and will respond to the Competition and Markets Authority’s report and recommendations shortly.</p><p> </p><p>The final report of the Insurance Fraud Task Force (January 2016) included a recommendation that the government should consider strengthening the enforcement powers of the Solicitors Regulation Authority. We are reviewing the position on this and considering what further action may be appropriate.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL6256 ; HL6257 ; HL6258 ; HL6260","2017-04-04T15:48:27.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713139/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713139/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713139/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-21","Solicitors: Prosecutions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have received any representations regarding the ability of legal regulators to bring prosecutions against solicitors for breaches of the law, and any proposals for that ability to be strengthened; and if so, whether they agree with those representations.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL6259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713140","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-04","<p>The government has not yet issued a consultation on making legal services regulators independent from their representative bodies, and will respond to the Competition and Markets Authority’s report and recommendations shortly.</p><p> </p><p>The final report of the Insurance Fraud Task Force (January 2016) included a recommendation that the government should consider strengthening the enforcement powers of the Solicitors Regulation Authority. We are reviewing the position on this and considering what further action may be appropriate.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL6256 ; HL6257 ; HL6258 ; HL6259","2017-04-04T15:48:27.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713140/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713140/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713140/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-21","Legal Profession: Regulation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the conclusion in the Competition and Markets Authority’s market study into legal services, published on 15 December 2016, that legal service regulators should be independent of their representative bodies as a "matter of principle"; and whether they have made any assessment of the possible benefits of such a move.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL6260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713592","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-27","<p>The Government has received representations from social care providers and charities, social care workers, and hon. Members writing on behalf of their constituents.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-27T09:21:25.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713592/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713592/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713592/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-21","Social Services: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what representations the Government has received on the applicability of the national minimum wage and the national living wage to staff who are asleep during a sleep-in shift at work.","false","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan","909497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713957","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-27","<p>Automatic enrolment was designed specifically to help those underrepresented in pension saving - including women.</p><p> </p><p>And encouragingly, in 2015 for the first time the proportion of eligible women (70%) participating in private sector workplace pensions was greater than the proportion of eligible men (69%).</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-03-27T15:57:27.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713957/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713957/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-21","Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps the Government is taking to encourage more women to enrol in pensions at a younger age.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","909494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713958","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-27","<p>We are currently preparing for a smooth and orderly exit from the EU and are confident we will be able to secure a deal that works in the mutual interests of both the UK and the rest of the European Union. We are considering various policy options and it would be wrong to set out further positions at this stage.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-27T16:20:40.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713958/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713958/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713958/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-21","Department for Work and Pensions: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the policy implications for his Department of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","909481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713959","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-27","<p>Women reaching State Pension age in 2016/17 are estimated to receive more State Pension on average over their lifetime than women ever have before.</p><p> </p><p>By 2030, over 3 million women stand to gain an average of £550 per year through the introduction of the new State Pension.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-03-27T16:17:37.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713959/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713959/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-21","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the financial effect on women of recent changes in the pension age","false","Biography information for Maria Caulfield","Lewes","Maria Caulfield","909488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712361","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-28","<p>Updated Single Departmental Plans will be published on gov.uk by the end of May 2017, once the formal business planning process across government has concluded.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-03-28T12:24:04.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712361/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712361/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-20","Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when each department plans to publish updated Single Departmental Plans.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","68504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712362","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-24","<p>All meetings between Ministers and newspapers and other media proprietors, editors and senior executives held in an official, social and political capacity are (and will continue to be) published on a quarterly basis.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-03-24T12:16:36.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712362/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712362/answer","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712362/answer/previousversion/41970","Biography information for Ben Gummer","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-20","George Osborne","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether future meetings between Ministers and the right hon. Member for Tatton will be required to be published in the Departments' transparency data concerning meetings with proprietors, editors and media executives after his appointment as editor of the London Evening Standard; and whether any such meetings will be exempt from declaration in such transparency data.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","68588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712363","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-27","<p>At the Budget on 8 March the Chancellor announced a new relief scheme for pubs with a rateable value below £100,000. Under the scheme, eligible pubs will receive a £1000 discount on rate bills. My Department will shortly consult on guidance which will include proposals on the eligibility criteria and other aspects of the scheme.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-27T14:51:37.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712363/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712363/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-20","Non-domestic Rates: Public Houses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to paragraph 4.5 of the Spring Budget 2017, what estimate the Government has made of the number of public houses that will be eligible for the £1,000 business rate discount in (a) Bedford and (b) Bedfordshire.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","68565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712364","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Treasury has not made an estimate of the number of jobs sustained by cryptocurrency trading and related services and does not currently have plans to do so.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-03-28T16:51:50.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712364/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712364/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-20","Cryptocurrencies: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate the number of jobs sustained by cryptocurrency trading and related services.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","68563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712365","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-28","<p>The information requested would be held by member states (or the UK businesses themselves) and is not held by HM Revenue and Customs.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-28T15:57:01.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712365/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712365/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-20","VAT: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much VAT was recovered by UK businesses from other EU member states under Articles 170 and 171 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC in each local authority area since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","68571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712366","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-23","<p>We are currently negotiating amendments to the Fourth Anti-Money Laundering Directive. These amendments will extend the scope of Directive (EU) 2015/849 to include virtual currency exchange platforms and custodian wallet providers, which will enable competent authorities to ensure virtual currency networks are mitigating the risks regarding money laundering and terrorist financing. There are no current plans to regulate distributed ledger technology.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-03-23T15:45:22.63Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712366/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712366/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-20","Cryptocurrencies and Distributed Ledger Technology: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to regulate distributed ledger technology and cryptocurrencies in the current Parliament.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","68581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712367","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-23","The total amount of VAT recovered by EU member state businesses from the Exchequer under Articles 170 and 171 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC in each year since 2010 is as follows:<p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Fiscal Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>VAT Recovered</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>Unavailable</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>£114,054,136.50</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>£91,034,004.22</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>£80,859,842.27</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>£40,093,982.14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>£87,374,709.60</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-23T17:26:02.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712367/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712367/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-20","VAT: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much VAT was recovered by EU member state businesses from the UK exchequer under Articles 170 and 171 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","68584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712369","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-18","<p>The Government set out its rationale for reforming the fees for grants of probate in its response to consultation on the fees published on Friday 24 February.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to providing a modern, world-leading justice system which is proportionate and accessible. The best way to protect access to justice is with a properly funded courts and tribunals service.</p><p> </p><p>Fees are necessary to support an effective courts and tribunals system that supports victims and vulnerable people, and is easy for ordinary people to use. In 2015/16, the Government spent around £1.9 billion on our courts and tribunals and recovered only around £700m through fees and other income. We do not believe that the taxpayer should continue to meet all of this cost.</p><p> </p><p>We are getting rid of flat fees and replacing them with a fair, banded, structure related to the value of the estate. This includes raising the fee threshold from £5,000 to £50,000 and lifting an extra 25,000 estates out of fees altogether.</p><p> </p><p>More than half of estates in England and Wales will pay no probate fee and over 90 per cent of estates will pay £1,000 or less. The fees will be implemented on a banded structure, increasing in line with estate values, meaning higher fees are paid by those who can afford to do so. No one will pay more than 1 per cent of the total estate value.</p><p> </p><p>Using the authoritative ONS projections, we have recently improved our estimates of the number of estates in England and Wales.</p><p> </p><p>With this more accurate data, we have produced a refreshed distribution of the estate values table. We have also updated our estimates to take account of HMRC’s most recent data on the distribution of estate values. <em> </em>These minor adjustments to Table 1 (page 11) of the consultation response do not alter the substance of, or rationale for, the proposals on which we consulted, or the Government’s decision to proceed with the changes. I have placed amended versions of the Government response to consultation in the libraries of the Houses.<em> </em></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Value of estate (before inheritance tax)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proportion of All estates in England and Wales</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proposed Fee</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Up to £50,000 or exempt from requiring a grant of probate</p></td><td><p>53%</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Exceeds £50,000 but does not exceed £300,000</p></td><td><p>25%</p></td><td><p>£300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Exceeds £300,000 but does not exceed £500,000</p></td><td><p>12%</p></td><td><p>£1,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Exceeds £500,000 but does not exceed £1m</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td><td><p>£4,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Exceeds £1m but does not exceed £1.6m</p></td><td><p>1%</p></td><td><p>£8,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Exceeds £1.6m but does not exceed £2m</p></td><td><p>0.3%</p></td><td><p>£12,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Above £2m</p></td><td><p>0.6%</p></td><td><p>£20,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-04-18T08:26:46.103Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712369/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712369/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Probate: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what her Department's rationale was for introducing a sliding scale of probate fees based on the worth of an estate.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","68494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712370","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-24","<p>Rateable values are set independently of ministers by the Valuation Office Agency. The Government has put in place a £3.6 billion package of transitional relief to support those businesses facing an increase. Additionally, my Department has been working closely with the Treasury to determine how best to provide further support to those businesses with the steepest increases.</p><p>A package of support was subsequently announced at the Budget on 8 March. It includes £110 million to support rate-payers losing small business rates relief and rural rate relief as a result of the 2017 revaluation, as well as a £300 million discretionary relief fund for local authorities to help individual businesses that are having the greatest difficulties paying increased rates bills.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-24T12:06:20.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712370/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712370/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-20","Non-domestic Rates: Pre-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the planned business rates rise on the nursery sector.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","68508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712371","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Treasury has direct responsibility only for the European Investment Bank. The department engages with a wide range of stakeholders including EU agencies. . We do not disaggregate the time and resource spent on this engagement.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-03-28T15:05:34.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712371/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712371/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-20","Treasury: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 7 March 2017 to Question 65651, on Treasury: Brexit, what (a) EU agencies and other organisations are within his Department's remit, (b) staff time was spent on engagement with those bodies and (c) financial resources were spent on engagement with those bodies in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","68530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712372","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Treasury has spent the following on advertising with the Evening Standard in each year since 2010:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Spend</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>£2,650</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>An advert was placed in the Evening Standard in 2010 for departmental recruitment purposes.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-03-23T15:43:59.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712372/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712372/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-20","Treasury: Evening Standard","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much his Department spent on advertising with the Evening Standard in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","68448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712373","Church Commissioners","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Church of England takes a flexible approach to yoga classes in church halls, with decisions left to the discretion of the local Parochial Church Council. Advice and guidance is available for parishes that are considering hiring their church hall out, which can be found here <a href="https://www.churchofengland.org/media/59302/NRM%20guidance.doc" target="_blank">https://www.churchofengland.org/media/59302/NRM%20guidance.doc</a></p><p> </p>","Meriden","Dame Caroline Spelman",,"2017-03-23T16:05:56.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712373/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712373/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712373/answer",,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2017-03-20","Churches: Yoga","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, what guidance is issued to churches on allowing church premises to be used for yoga classes.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","68543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712374","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-23","<p>My Department will consult on guidance on the Pubs Relief Scheme shortly. The consultation will include proposals on the eligibility criteria and other aspects of the scheme.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-23T14:29:47.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712374/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712374/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-20","Licensed Premises: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 16 March 2017 to Question 67412, on licensed premises: non-domestic rates, when he plans to publish the consultation on the eligibility criteria for the discount for eligible pubs.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","68550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712375","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-28","<p>My department engages with a range of stakeholders, including EU agencies. No EU agencies are directly within the department’s remit. We do not disaggregate the time and resource spent on this engagement.</p><p> </p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2017-03-28T16:36:03.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712375/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712375/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-20","Department for Communities and Local Government: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 7 March 2017 to Question 65636, on Department for Communities and Local Government: Brexit, what (a) EU agencies and other organisations are within his Department's remit, (b) staff time was spent on engagement with those bodies and (c) financial resources were spent on engagement with those bodies in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","68533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712376","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-23","<p>Social letting agencies can support vulnerable people and people on low incomes to access and sustain tenancies in the private rented sector. We want to prevent people reaching crisis point, and for those who are already homeless to be able to move out of temporary accommodation or hostels to a settled home as quickly as possible. There are a number of different models of social letting agencies and in the Housing White Paper we set out our interest in exploring the relative effectiveness of these different models with the aim of securing more housing for households who would otherwise struggle – providing security for landlords and support for tenants.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-23T11:03:51.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712376/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712376/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-20","Social Rented Housing: Letting Agents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if his Department will publish a definition of the term social lettings agencies as used in the white paper, Fixing our broken housing market, published in February 2017.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","68432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712377","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-23","<p>We are currently supporting twenty-four locally-led garden towns, cities and villages in places where communities want them. These have the potential to deliver over 200,000 homes.</p><p>We remain committed to supporting other places with ambitious proposals for new locally-led garden communities at scale.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-23T11:09:14.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712377/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712377/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-20","Garden Communities: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of permitting the construction of 15 new garden city-style developments of 100,000 homes.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","68582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712378","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-23","<p>We currently have no plans to devolve additional fiscal powers to local councils.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-23T14:29:17.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712378/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712378/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-20","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will devolve additional fiscal powers to local councils to fund social care.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","68580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712379","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-27","<p>Doping is unacceptable in any level of sport. It is important that all involved in sport play their part in educating participants about the dangers of doping, both in terms of the damage it does to sport's integrity but also the health risks to individuals as well. There is still more that sports governing bodies can do on this front, working alongside UK Anti-Doping, to help promote clean and fair sport at all levels.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-03-27T11:21:16.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712379/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712379/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-20","Sports: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans her Department has to tackle doping in amateur competitive sports.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","68575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712380","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-23","<p>Government is committed to encouraging more people to engage in sport and physical activity, regardless of their background or level of ability.</p><p> </p><p>Government's Sporting Future strategy published in December 2015 set out that, in future, public investment in sport and physical activity will be based on the contribution that organisations can make to five broad outcomes: Physical Wellbeing; Mental Wellbeing; Individual Development; Social and Community Development; and Economic Development.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2010 Sport England has invested over £4.7 million of National Lottery money in projects and facilities to get more people mountain biking. Sport England will continue to work with British Cycling to ensure that more people from all backgrounds are encouraged to take up Mountain Biking and to enjoy the benefits it brings.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-03-23T16:34:08.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712380/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712380/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-20","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans her Department has to promote mountain biking as a sport.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","68586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712381","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-23","<p>Independent sources such as thinkbroadband (http://labs.thinkbroadband.com/local/) show UK superfast broadband coverage, defined as premises having access to speeds of more than 24Mbps, is now over 92%. The further contracted delivery from publicly-funded projects plus commercial plans from providers mean that the government is confident that 95% coverage can be reached by December 2017.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-23T16:37:03.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712381/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712381/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-20","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the UK Digital Strategy 2017, published on 1 March 2017 by her Department, if she will publish the evidential basis for the statement that superfast broadband is on track to reach 95 per cent of UK premises by December 2017; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","68607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712382","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-23","<p>It is not our practice to publish ministerial correspondence.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-23T16:09:19.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712382/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712382/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-20","BBC Board: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if she will publish the correspondence between her Department and the Welsh Government on the issue of the appointment of a Welsh member to the BBC Board.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","68445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712383","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-23","<p>Government is committed to supporting everyone to get active and participation in swimming has an important role to play.</p><p>Sport England has invested more than £40,000 of National Lottery funding in a Kirklees swimming programme and since 2010 has invested £1.5 million of Lottery funding in swimming in West Yorkshire.</p><p>Since 2010, Sport England has invested £35,407,363 of National Lottery money has been invested in a range of swimming projects across Greater London, including £34,442,800 in swimming in Newham and the London Aquatics Centre.</p><p>Sport England is also in discussion with the Amateur Swimming Association regarding the investment it will be making in swimming for the 2017-21 period.</p><p>Sporting Future set out the Government's commitment to ensuring that no child left school unable to swim and commissioned the Amateur Swimming Association's Swim Group to undertake a review. The Group is finalising its report and will be sharing its findings with government shortly.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","68402","2017-03-23T16:35:39.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712383/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712383/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-20","Swimming: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to increase the number of (a) children and (b) adults who swim regularly in (i) Greater London and (ii) the London Borough of Newham.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","68462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712384","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-28","<p>There are no plans to amend section 10 of the Charities Act 2011 to apply charity law to ecclesiastical corporations. Ecclesiastical corporations are regulated under Canon law of the Church of England.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-03-28T10:52:36.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712384/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712384/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712384/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-20","Charities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Civil Society plans to amend section 10 of the Charities Act 2011 to define ecclesiastical corporations as charities.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","68476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712385","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Government has no plans to review restrictions placed on digital locks, otherwise known as Technical Protection Measures (TPMs). The restrictions placed on the circumvention of TPMs in the EU Information Society Directive derive from the WIPO Copyright Treaty (Article 11) and the WIPO Performances and Phonograms Treaty (Article 18). As a party to these treaties, the UK’s obligations will remain in place after the UK leaves the EU.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-03-23T16:04:11.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712385/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712385/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-20","Copyright: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether his Department plans to review the restrictions paced on digital locks under the EU Copyright Directive as a result of Britain's decision to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","68480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712386","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-03","<p>The following EU agencies and other organisations are within DCMS’ remit:<br></p><ul><li>European Union Agency for Network and Information Security (ENISA)</li><li>The Office of the Body of European Regulators for Electronic Communications (the BEREC Office)</li><li>European Regulators Group for Audiovisual Media Services (ERGAMS)</li><li>Data Protection Supervisor</li><li>European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI)</li><li>Education, Audiovisual and Culture Executive Agency (EACEA)</li></ul>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-04-03T08:31:10.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712386/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712386/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-20","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 7 March 2017 to Question 65637, non Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Brexit, what (a) EU agencies and other organisations are within her Department's remit, (b) staff time was spent on engagement with those bodies and (c) financial resources were spent on engagement with those bodies in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","68518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712387","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-23","<p>The local authorities that are being or have been investigated are Lancashire, Lambeth, Southampton, Harrow, Sheffield, Newcastle, Lincolnshire, Bolton, Brent, Isle of Wight, Lewisham, Somerset, Gloucestershire, Doncaster and Surrey. In respect of Lancashire, Lambeth and Southampton these investigations are on-going and no final decision has been made. With regard to Harrow, Sheffield, Newcastle, Lincolnshire, Bolton, London Borough of Brent, Isle of Wight, Lewisham the Secretary of State decided with each of these cases not to direct a local inquiry. In the case of Somerset and Gloucestershire no action was required as both local authorities reverted to their original library service provision following successful judicial review challenges and with respect to Doncaster and Surrey no action was taken.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-03-23T14:36:20.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712387/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712387/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-20","Public Libraries: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 20 March 2017 to Question 68114, on public libraries: complaints, which 15 local authorities have been investigated since 2010; and what the outcomes were of those investigations.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","68553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712388","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-27","<p>As of 21 March 2017, there are 27 Royal Navy personnel in training alongside the US military to maintain aircraft carrier skills, under the Long Lead Specialist Skills Programme.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-27T15:16:34.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712388/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712388/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Aircraft Carriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many Royal Navy personnel are currently training alongside the US military to maintain aircraft carrier skills.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","68487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712389","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) engages with a wide range of EU institutions and agencies including EU Military Staff, the European Security and Defence College, the European Defence Agency, the European Institute for Security Studies and the EU Satellite Centre.</p><p>The lead for engagement with these organisations is the joint MOD/Foreign and Commonwealth Office Euro-Atlantic Security Policy Team and engagement takes place with a range of stakeholders. We do not disaggregate the time and resource spent on this engagement.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-03-28T16:33:20.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712389/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712389/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Ministry of Defence: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 6 March 2017 to Question 65638, on Ministry of Defence: Brexit, what (a) EU agencies and other organisations are within his Department's remit, (b) staff time was spent on engagement with those bodies and (c) financial resources were spent on engagement with those bodies in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","68523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712390","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-27","<p>The Naval Service and Royal Air Force, like many employers in the UK aviation sector, utilise a combination of remunerative and non-remunerative measures to aid the retention of pilots within the Service.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-27T15:13:58.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712390/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712390/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Armed Forces: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to retain Royal Navy and RAF pilots.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","68488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712391","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-27","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 7 February 2017 to Question 62463 to the hon. Member for Portsmouth South (Flick Drummond).</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-27T15:14:38.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712391/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712391/answer","62463_WQnA_extract_on_HMS_Queen_Elizabeth.pdf","62463_WQnA_extract_on_HMS_Queen_Elizabeth.pdf","62463 - WQnA extract on HMS Queen Elizabeth","62463 - WQnA extract on HMS Queen Elizabeth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712391/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","HMS Queen Elizabeth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on what date the inaugural sailing of the first Queen Elizabeth class aircraft carrier is planned to take place.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","68489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712392","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-27","<p>The Royal Navy employs a range of mechanisms to attract and develop engineers including apprenticeship schemes and staged remunerative awards, as well as an active engagement in a University Technical Colleges affiliation programme aimed at assisting in the development of technically able young people.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-27T15:20:17.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712392/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712392/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Aircraft Carriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to tackle the shortage of engineers needed to support Royal Navy carrier strike capability.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","68490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712393","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-23","<p>The number of Ministry of Defence Disposal Services Authority (DSA) personnel that visited LEYAL Ship Recycling Ltd in each of the last five years is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of DSA Staff</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These visits were made to prepare audit reports on the ships recycled. The reports are published on the gov.uk website at:</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/groups/disposal-services-authority#ship-recycling" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/groups/disposal-services-authority#ship-recycling</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-23T16:05:33.843Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712393/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712393/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Ministry of Defence: Leyal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many of his Department's personnel have visited LEYAL Ship Recycling Ltd in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","68546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712394","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-23","<p>There are no LEYAL Ship Recycling Ltd employees seconded to the Ministry of Defence.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-23T16:12:38.083Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712394/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712394/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Ministry of Defence: Leyal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many staff of LEYAL Ship Recycling Ltd are working on secondment at his Department.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","68544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712395","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-23","<p>Information about sale receipts received from LEYAL Ship Recycling Ltd in each of the last five years is contained in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Value of Sale Receipts per year (£ million)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2.15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>8.86</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2.15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2.13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>2.88</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-23T16:12:12.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712395/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712395/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Ministry of Defence: Leyal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what fees his Department has received from LEYAL Ship Recycling Ltd in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","68545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712396","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-23","<p>HMS QUEEN ELIZABETH is planned to achieve an initial operating capability for Carrier Strike in December 2020.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-23T16:09:23.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712396/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712396/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","HMS Queen Elizabeth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he plans that HMS Queen Elizabeth will achieve carrier strike capability.","false","Biography information for Wayne David","Caerphilly","Wayne David","68481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712397","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-23","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 1 February 2017 to Question 62463.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-23T16:06:07.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712397/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712397/answer","Hansard Extract -  Wednesday 1 February 2017 HOC 62463.docx","Hansard Extract -  Wednesday 1 February 2017 HOC 62463.docx","HMS  Queen Elizabeth","HMS  Queen Elizabeth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712397/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","HMS Queen Elizabeth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what date has been set for the inaugural sailing of the HMS Queen Elizabeth.","false","Biography information for Wayne David","Caerphilly","Wayne David","68482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712398","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-27","<p>We already have in place robust governance processes that reflect the strategic importance of the Carrier Enabled Power Projection Programme. These governance arrangements are being continuously refined to ensure that this strategic capability is directed and employed appropriately.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-27T15:19:05.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712398/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712398/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Aircraft Carriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to paragraph 22, page 13 of the National Audit Office report, Delivering Carrier Strike, published on 16 March 2017, what steps his Department is taking to set out arrangements for long-term leadership and oversight of Carrier Enabled Power Projection capability.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","68470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712399","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-27","<p>We welcome the National Audit Office's recognition of the progress we have made towards delivering the Carrier Strike capability. We will examine the recommendations and report back progress against them in accordance with normal process.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-27T15:18:23.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712399/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712399/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Aircraft Carriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to paragraph 22, page 13 of the National Audit Office report, Delivering Carrier Strike, published on 16 March 2017, what assessment he has made of the implications for his Department's policies of that report's recommendation.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","68472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712400","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-27","<p>The Ministry of Defence is ensuring that the thousands of personnel operating in the defence acquisition system have the necessary skills and competences, including those in commercial roles. In particular, our Commercial Professionalism Programme is currently aiming to increase the professional skills of the commercial function, enabling us to grow and retain our own talent. We have already developed training specifically targeting the skills gaps identified in contract management, with 30 courses scheduled per year on the subject.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-27T15:15:20.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712400/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712400/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Aircraft Carriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to paragraph 19, page 12 of the National Audit Office report, Delivering Carrier Strike, published on 16 March 2017, what steps he is taking to address the long-standing skills gaps in his Department's contract management teams.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","68473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712401","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-27","<p>There are no plans to procure additional helicopters at this time.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-27T15:19:41.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712401/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712401/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Aircraft Carriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to paragraph 1.9, page 16 of the National Audit Office report, Delivering Carrier Strike, published on 16 March 2017, whether he plans to procure additional helicopters to increase the number of Crownsnest radar-enabled aircraft available.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","68474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712402","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-23","<p>We have a broad range of senior military personnel and civil servants routinely engaged with their US counterparts in developing UK Carrier Enabled Power Projection doctrine, and assessing interoperability requirements and opportunities.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-23T16:08:51.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712402/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712402/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Aircraft Carriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many Royal Navy senior personnel are working with the US Navy to develop a UK-specific Carrier Enabled Power Projection doctrine and assessing interoperability.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","68463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712403","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-23","<p>The UK has Armed Forces personnel assigned to US Navy Carrier Strike Groups. I am withholding the information as its disclosure would, or would be likely to prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-23T16:04:58.653Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712403/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712403/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Aircraft Carriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many UK armed forces personnel are deployed to an operationally deployed US Navy carrier strike group.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","68464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712404","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-23","<p>The UK has Armed Forces personnel assigned to various commands in the US. I am withholding the information as its disclosure would, or would be likely to prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-23T16:07:07.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712404/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712404/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","USA: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many UK armed forces personnel are deployed with (a) US Fleet Forces Command, (b) US Pacific Fleet, (c) US Naval Forces Europe - Naval Forces Africa, (d) US Naval Forces Central Command, (e) US Naval Forces Southern Command, (f) US Naval Special Warfare Command, (g) US Navy Operational Test and Evaluation Force, (h) US Navy Naval Warfare Command, (i) Military Sealift Command and (j) US Navy Naval Reserve Forces.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","68465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712405","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-23","<p>There are currently no US Navy personnel working in the Development, Concepts and Doctrine Centre.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-23T16:06:35.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712405/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712405/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Aircraft Carriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many US Navy personnel are working at his Department's Development, Concept and Doctrine Centre in support of developing a UK-specific Carrier Enabled Power Projection doctrine.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","68466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712406","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-27","<p>There is no requirement at this time to increase the planned numbers of UK F-35 Lightning pilots being trained in the US.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-27T15:16:01.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712406/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712406/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether plans exist to increase the number of Royal Navy and Royal Air Force F-35 pilots trained in the US above the numbers already planned.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","68436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712407","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-27","<p>The approved cost of the Queen Elizabeth Class programme remains at £6.212 billion. The Department keeps costs within the programme under very close scrutiny, and industry is incentivised to manage cost pressures.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-27T15:22:43.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712407/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712407/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Aircraft Carriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to minimise cost increases to the Carrier Strike programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","68458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712408","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-27","<p>We remain committed to the F-35 programme and, as per the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015, we plan to buy 138 Lightning aircraft over the life of the programme. The Department has appropriate contingency in place to ensure that the F-35 programme delivers on time and to the approved cost.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-03-27T15:13:18.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712408/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712408/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what contingency provision his Department has made for changes in the cost to the UK of Lightning II jets as a result of changes in the number of orders for such aircraft worldwide.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","68430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712409","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-23","<p>This information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-03-23T16:08:20.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712409/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712409/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-20","Armed Forces: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department has spent on each Substitute Service (a) Family and (b) Single Accommodation in each year from 2010 to 2017.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","68440"
